id', pattern: /AKIA[A-Z0-9]{16}/g },\n  { name: 'aws_secret', pattern: /(?:aws_secret_access_key|AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY)\\s*[=:]\\s*[A-Za-z0-9/+=]{40}/gi },\n  { name: 'bearer_token', pattern: /Bearer\\s+[a-zA-Z0-9._-]{20,}/g },\n  { name: 'url_password', pattern: /:\\/\\/([^:]+):([^@]{8,})@/g },\n  { name: 'slack_token', pattern: /xox[bpars]-[a-zA-Z0-9-]{10,}/g },\n  { name: 'google_key', pattern: /AIza[a-zA-Z0-9_-]{35}/g },\n  { name: 'stripe_key', pattern: /[rs]k_(?:live|test)_[a-zA-Z0-9]{20,}/g },\n  { name: 'base64_secret', pattern: /(?:key|secret|password|token|credential)\\s*[=:]\\s*[A-Za-z0-9+/]{40,}={0,2}/gi },\n];\n\n/**\n * Scrub sensitive patterns from text output.\n * Returns the scrubbed text along with redaction statistics.\n */\nexport function scrub(text: string, config?: ScrubberConfig): ScrubResult {\n  if (config?.enabled === false) {\n    return { scrubbed: text, redactionCount: 0, redactedTypes: [] };\n  }\n\n  let result = text;\n  let totalRedactions = 0;\n  const typesFound = new Set<string>();\n\n  const patterns = [...DEFAULT_PATTERNS, ...(config?.customPatterns ?? [])];\n\n  for (const { name, pattern } of patterns) {\n    // Reset regex lastIndex for global patterns\n    pattern.lastIndex = 0;\n\n    const matches = result.match(pattern);\n    if (matches) {\n      totalRedactions += matches.length;\n      typesFound.add(name);\n\n      if (name === 'url_password') {\n        // For URL passwords, preserve the URL structure\n        result = result.replace(pattern, '://$1:[REDACTED:url_password]@');\n      } else {\n        result = result.replace(pattern, `[REDACTED:${name}]`);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return {\n    scrubbed: result,\n    redactionCount: totalRedactions,\n    redactedTypes: Array.from(typesFound),\n  };\n}\n","numLines":67,"startLine":1,"totalLines":67}}}
[2026-03-18T12:01:55.030Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CjuF88Vk5skFr1e3Funj7Z","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the Worker Execution Environment. Let me analyze the structural constraints before generating ideas.\n\n**Structural Constraint Analysis:**\n\n1. **Single-execution-per-worker limitation**: The worker can only handle ONE execution at a time (`isBusy()` check, single `currentExecutionId`). Every worker process maps to exactly one Claude CLI process. This means scaling requires linearly adding worker processes, each with full OS-level overhead (bwrap namespace, proxy, credential files). The worker is fundamentally a 1:1 process wrapper.\n\n2. **Process-per-execution model with full CLI spawn**: Each execution spawns a brand new Claude CLI process from scratch via `child_process.spawn()`. \n\nThere's no session reuse or warm-start—every execution incurs the full cold-start penalty of CLI initialization, and the sandbox directory gets created and destroyed with each run.\n\n3. **Stdout line-parsing as the sole communication channel**: The entire worker<->Claude communication happens through stdout line parsing with regex-based JSON extraction. The parser uses `JSON_BLOCK_PATTERN = /\\{[^{}]*(?:\\{[^{}]*\\}[^{}]*)*\\}/g` which only handles 2-level nesting. Protocol events are embedded within assistant message text blocks and extracted via string matching. This is fragile and bandwidth-limited.\n\n4. **Network**\n\nNetwork policy enforcement relies on either full namespace isolation with bwrap or an HTTP CONNECT proxy that can only filter by host:port, not content or protocol—and it gets bypassed for direct connections outside a namespace. If a worker crashes mid-execution, the work is completely lost with no checkpoint mechanism or ability to resume on a different worker.\n\nThe execution engine itself is the core product—the ability to run AI agents in sandboxed environments with fine-grained network control and real-time event streaming is what drives the value. bwrap for Linux sandboxing and WebSocket for real-time communication are the right architectural choices here.\n\nThe real structural bottleneck is spawning a new CLI process for every execution. I'm thinking about replacing that with persistent Claude CLI processes in warm pools that accept work via stdin, which would eliminate the cold-start penalty. Instead of parsing fragile regex patterns from stdout, I could use a dedicated IPC channel like a Unix domain socket or named pipe to get structured communication without the JSON nesting limitations. And rather than one worker per execution, I could use lightweight containers or cgroups to let a single worker handle multiple executions simultaneously.\n\nI'm also considering checkpoint/restore mechanisms using CRIU to snapshot running executions and move them between workers for zero-downtime deployments, or replacing bwrap entirely with WebAssembly sandboxing through something like Wasmtime to get cross-platform isolation with better capability control. Narrowing down to the strongest approaches: a warm process pool with session multiplexing would directly address the cold-start problem. Looking back at the actual constraints in the codebase—each execution spawns a fresh Claude CLI instance with sandbox setup and credential injection, and the JSON parser only handles two levels of nesting—these are the specific bottlenecks I need to address rather than generic optimization advice.\n\nThe first idea is to maintain a pool of pre-warmed sandboxes with persistent Claude CLI processes, so instead of cold-starting everything from scratch on each assignment, I can inject the prompt into an already-running process and measure the latency improvement with a prototype pool of a few sandboxes.\n\nThe second approach is to replace the regex-based stdout parsing with a typed IPC channel like a Unix domain socket, since the current JSON pattern regex can't handle deeply nested payloads and becomes a bottleneck as the protocol grows more complex.\n\nThe third idea involves using CRIU to snapshot execution state for fault tolerance, though there's a constraint I'm about to examine.\n\nIf a worker crashes mid-execution, everything is lost—for long-running personas this is a critical reliability gap. I'm considering CRIU checkpoints that can be restored on another worker to resume from where it failed, though the interaction between CRIU and bwrap sandboxing could be tricky.\n\nThe fourth approach tackles scaling by moving away from the one-process-per-execution model, since each worker carries overhead from WebSocket connections, Node.js runtime memory, and orchestration costs.\n\nInstead of spinning up separate workers, I'd use cgroup v2 to run multiple concurrent executions within a single worker process, each with isolated memory and CPU limits. The tradeoff is added complexity in cgroup management and potential resource contention between slots, but it could significantly reduce per-execution overhead at scale.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":24474,"cache_read_input_tokens":23823,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":24474},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5ccd4a17-e6fd-4409-a07f-eea32410d852","uuid":"f2d6c931-e396-4038-863b-76349f215479"}
